description.narrative: 1. ‘4-in-1’ ABC/3TC/LPV/r: develop, register and develop access to a solid, taste-masked, first-line LPV/r-based fixed-dose formulation with two nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NRTIs), lamivudine and abacavir. 2. ‘2-in-1’ LPV/r pellets, with dual NRTI: evaluate the effectiveness of LPV/r pellets, given with two NRTIs (either AZT/3TC or ABC/3TC), in an implementation study in HIV-infected infants and young children who cannot swallow pills. 3. Super-booster therapy for paediatric HIV/tuberculosis (TB): support implementation of and access to a stand-alone pharmacokinetic ritonavir booster formulation, to be added to any protease inhibitor-based paediatric ARV regimen for the treatment of HIV/TB co-infected children. 4. cryptococcal meningitis: this project aims to deliver a simpler, sustained-release formulation of flucytosine adapted for use in resource-limited settings.

DNDi aims to help end the neglect of paediatric HIV by developing optimal child-friendly antiretroviral formulations for children living with HIV with a special focus on infants and young children who are at the highest risk of dying without treatment. The cryptococcal meningitis project aims to advance the development of sustained-release flucytosine to simplify inpatient and outpatient treatment of cryptococcal infections
